laralux (0.8.1-1) UNRELEASED; urgency=medium

  * fix: stopping a site process now kills its whole process group, so commands
    that fork children (npm run dev, artisan serve, queue job subprocesses) no
    longer leave orphans running after the UI reports them stopped. Applies to
    managed services too.

 -- thotam <thanhtamtotaa@gmail.com>  Tue, 21 Jul 2026 14:30:00 +0700

laralux (0.8.0-1) UNRELEASED; urgency=medium

  * security: files under a site's .well-known are no longer executed or served
    as source, at any path depth, while ACME and OAuth/OIDC discovery still
    reach the app.
  * services report Running only after a health check passes, so a site's
    Procfile worker no longer starts before the database is accepting
    connections (queue:work Connection refused on boot).
  * Procfile processes are supervised: crashed processes restart with a
    1s/5s/15s/30s backoff, give up after 5 consecutive failures, and reset
    after 30s of uptime; a process stopped by hand is never restarted.
  * fix: starting the stack from the tray no longer blocks the UI thread.

 -- thotam <thanhtamtotaa@gmail.com>  Tue, 21 Jul 2026 12:00:00 +0700

laralux (0.7.0-1) UNRELEASED; urgency=medium

  * proxy sites: an optional project folder can now be attached to a
    reverse-proxy site, which lets its Procfile processes run (e.g. the
    upstream dev server) and unhides Open folder / Open terminal / the project
    path for it. The folder never becomes a document root.
  * a proxy whose folder has gone missing is kept with a warning instead of
    being skipped, so routing and HTTPS never depend on the folder.
  * fix: read_procfile no longer picks up a stray Procfile from the process
    working directory when a site root is empty.
  * packaging: the released .deb is now built on Ubuntu 22.04 rather than
    24.04. ${shlibs:Depends} pins the package to the build host's glibc, so
    the 24.04 build (glibc 2.39) could not be installed on Ubuntu 22.04
    (2.35) or Debian 12 bookworm (2.36); the 22.04 build covers those too.

 -- thotam <thanhtamtotaa@gmail.com>  Tue, 21 Jul 2026 09:50:00 +0700

laralux (0.6.0-1) UNRELEASED; urgency=medium

  * public domains: each site can serve real domains reverse-proxied from an
    upstream server that terminates public TLS (e.g. Let's Encrypt). Served on
    both port 80 and 443 with no redirect, using the site's mkcert cert on 443
    (SAN extended to cover the public domains; upstream sets proxy_ssl_verify
    off). Public domains are excluded from the managed /etc/hosts block. Added
    via the site row menu -> Public domains, with a badge on the site card.

 -- thotam <thanhtamtotaa@gmail.com>  Wed, 15 Jul 2026 19:00:00 +0700

laralux (0.5.0-1) UNRELEASED; urgency=medium

  * packaging: debian/rules is the single source of truth; the release
    workflow builds and publishes the .deb via dpkg-buildpackage instead of
    tauri-action, so local and CI builds match. GUI binary installs to
    /usr/bin/laralux-desktop, desktop entry com.laralux.desktop, icon
    com.laralux.png.
  * identifier: shortened com.laralux.linux -> com.laralux across the runtime
    autostart entry, the dev desktop entry, and the packaged desktop/icon.

 -- thotam <thanhtamtotaa@gmail.com>  Wed, 01 Jul 2026 09:00:00 +0700

laralux (0.4.3-1) UNRELEASED; urgency=medium

  * dns: stop the recurring polkit password prompt on nearly every boot to
    write the systemd-resolved drop-in. CoreDNS port jitter (a just-killed
    stale instance still held the port when the next port was picked, bumping
    onto a higher one and baking it into the drop-in) made the drop-in differ
    from the port chosen on the next clean boot. laralux now waits for the
    canonical port to be released before picking and reuses the port already
    recorded in the drop-in when the canonical one is busy, keeping the
    drop-in stable across restarts and reboots.

 -- thotam <thanhtamtotaa@gmail.com>  Wed, 01 Jul 2026 08:00:00 +0700

laralux (0.4.2-1) UNRELEASED; urgency=medium

  * nginx: ship a mime.types map and include it, fixing sites that rendered
    as unstyled HTML because every asset was served as octet-stream and
    browsers rejected the CSS/ES modules.
  * nginx: full fastcgi_params (REDIRECT_STATUS, REQUEST_SCHEME, HTTPS,
    SERVER_PORT, ...) plus the httpoxy guard HTTP_PROXY "".
  * nginx: per-site HTTP/2, stronger TLS (TLSv1.2/1.3, cipher set, session
    cache), gzip, sendfile/keepalive, charset utf-8, server_tokens off,
    dotfile denial, and an immutable cache for Laravel /build/ assets.

 -- thotam <thanhtamtotaa@gmail.com>  Tue, 30 Jun 2026 17:30:00 +0700

laralux (0.4.1-1) UNRELEASED; urgency=medium

  * CoreDNS: bind a dedicated port (15353) with free-port fallback instead of
    5353, which collided with avahi-daemon's mDNS and crash-looped the resolver
    (tray icon stuck red).
  * TLS: pre-seed the Chromium NSS database with the bundled certutil so the
    mkcert CA is trusted on first browser launch (was ERR_CERT_AUTHORITY_INVALID
    for *.dev when the browser profile appeared after setup).

 -- thotam <thanhtamtotaa@gmail.com>  Tue, 30 Jun 2026 16:00:00 +0700

laralux (0.4.0-1) UNRELEASED; urgency=medium

  * Setup: disable distro nginx/mariadb/redis units individually and skip any
    that aren't installed, so missing units no longer fail the whole step.
  * Setup: install the mkcert CA into the system trust store under privilege
    escalation (CAROOT pinned to the user CA), fixing "mkcert -install (system)
    failed" when run unprivileged with no TTY.
  * Setup: run all privileged steps under a single authorization prompt.

 -- thotam <thanhtamtotaa@gmail.com>  Tue, 30 Jun 2026 10:00:00 +0700

